The Nautilus DevOps team continues to explore serverless architecture by setting up another Lambda function. 
This time, the task must be completed using the AWS Console to familiarize the team with the web interface. 
The function will return a custom greeting and demonstrate the capabilities of AWS Lambda effectively.

Create Python Script: Create a Python script named lambda_function.py with a function that returns the body Welcome to KKE AWS Labs! and status code 200.

Zip the Python Script: Zip the script into a file named function.zip.

Create Lambda Function: Create a Lambda function named datacenter-lambda-cli using the zipped file and specify Python as the runtime.

IAM Role: Use the IAM role named lambda_execution_role.


Solution : 

1. Create the Python Script (lambda_function.py)

Open a text editor or IDE (like VS Code, PyCharm, etc.).

Paste the following Python code into the editor:

import json

def lambda_handler(event, context):
    response = {
        'statusCode': 200,
        'body': json.dumps({'message': 'Welcome to KKE AWS Labs!'})
    }
    return response
Save the file as lambda_function.py. Make sure the file extension is .py.

2. Zip the Python Script (function.zip)

Open a Terminal/Command Prompt: Navigate to the directory where you saved lambda_function.py.

Zip the file: Use the following command to create the ZIP archive:

zip function.zip lambda_function.py

This will create a file named function.zip in the same directory.

3. Create the Lambda Function Using the AWS CLI

Login to AWS CLI: (If you haven't already)

aws configure
Follow the prompts to configure your AWS credentials (Access Key ID, Secret Access Key, Region, and Output Format).

Create the Lambda Function: Use the following command. Replace the placeholder values with your actual values.

~ on ☁️  (us-east-1) ➜  aws lambda create-function \
    --function-name datacenter-lambda-cli \
    --runtime python3.9 \
    --role arn:aws:iam::363553714012:role/lambda_execution_role \
    --handler lambda_function.lambda_handler \
    --zip-file fileb://function.zip

--function-name datacenter-lambda-cli: This sets the name of your Lambda function.
--runtime python3.9: Specifies the Python runtime. You can change this if you have a different Python version.
--role lambda_execution_role: Crucially, this specifies the IAM role. You must have this role already created in AWS.
--handler lambda_function.lambda_handler: This tells Lambda where to find the function within the ZIP file.
--zip-file fileb://function.zip: This specifies the path to the ZIP file.

4. Verify the Lambda Function Creation

Get Function Details: After the Lambda function is created, you can check its configuration:

aws lambda get-function --function-name datacenter-lambda-cli


on ☁️  (us-east-1) ➜  aws iam list-roles| grep "lambda_execution_role"
            "RoleName": "lambda_execution_role",
            "Arn": "arn:aws:iam::363553714012:role/lambda_execution_role",

if the role not created  follow the below steps 

# 1. Login to AWS CLI (if you haven't already)
# 2. Create the IAM Role
aws iam create-role \
    --role-name lambda_execution_role \
    --description "Role for Lambda function execution"

# 3. Attach the Lambda Execution Policy
aws iam attach-role-policy \
    --role-name lambda_execution_role \
    --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole

# 4. Verify Role Creation
aws iam get-role --role-name lambda_execution_role




